We don't know that much about the new Tesla Gigafactory in Austin, TX but we do know some things about the similar Gigafactories in Germany and Shanghai. The Austin facility is projected to produce a similar number of vehicles once in full swing (https://www.tesla.com/sites/default/files/blog_attachments/gigafactory.pdf). However, Tesla’s TOTAL vehicle production will probably amount to about 500,000, in 2020 which is far less than the capacity of each Gigafactory (https://www.statista.com/statistics/715421/tesla-quarterly-vehicle-production/). This is due to a few factors, most importantly the availability of lithium-ion batteries.

Interestingly enough, a recent announcement from Australian mining firm Piedmont Lithium has revealed Tesla has signed a five-year deal to acquire spodumene from a mine in North Carolina. In its press release, Piedmont noted its Tesla deal represents about one-third of the expected 160,000 tonnes per annum that’s expected to be produced at its North Carolina mine. This deal will likely supply Tesla with 8,000 tonnes of lithium hydroxide a year, starting between July 2022 and July 2023.

I think building this factory and then ironing out all of the production and assembly line kinks will simply take time. Also humans are generally overly optimistic about how quickly they can complete tasks and projects. This can be backed-up by Tesla and Musk-things generally having historically overrun anticipated timeframes. Therefore I wouldn't be surprised if the factory and production process doesn't get completed until late or after 2022, meaning a zero or few trucks being produced. If however the factory and production process is finalised well before the end of 2022, they could/will ramp-up production quite significantly, and will be producing at a decent rate by end-2022. Therefore I think more chance of over 100K trucks being made if the factory is completed with enough time left in 2022. I don't think demand or actual delivery will be much of an issue or inhibitor once production is underway, and so anticipate the timing of factory completion being the primary variable.
